t in form from those which are added onthe diagonal sides of the octagon.a. First Class.The Chapel_ "degli Angeli," _at
Florence, built only to a height ofabout 20 feet by Brunellesco, may be considered as the prototype ofthis group; and, i
ndeed it probably suggested it. The fact that wesee in MS. B. 11b (Pl. XCIV, No. 3) by the side of Brunellesco'splan for
 the Basilica of Sto. Spirito at Florence, a plan almostidentical with that of the_ Capella degli Angeli, _confirms this
supposition. Only two small differences, or we may say improvements,have been introduced by Leonardo. Firstly the back o
f the chapelscontains a third niche, and each angle of the Octagon a foldedpilaster like those in Bramante's_ Sagrestia
di S. M. presso SanSatiro _at Milan, instead of an interval between the two pilastersas seen in the Battistero at Floren
ce and in the Sacristy of Sto.Spirito in the same town and also in the above named chapel byBrunellesco.The first set of
