s explain that the sun looks larger as it sets,because the eye always sees it through a denser atmosphere, allegingthat
objects seen through mist or through water appear larger. Tothese I reply: No; because objects seen through a mist are s
imilarin colour to those at a distance; but not being similarly diminishedthey appear larger. Again, nothing increases i
n size in smoothwater; and the proof of this may be seen by throwing a light on aboard placed half under water. But the
reason why the sun lookslarger is that every luminous body appears larger in proportion asit is more remote. [Footnote:
