89 AD. Dr. H. MULLER- STRUBING writes to me asfollows on this subject: "With reference to Rhodes Ross says (_Reiseauf de
n Griechischen Inseln, III_ 70 _ff_. 1840), that ancienthistory affords instances of severe earthquakes at Rhodes, among
others one in the second year of the 138th Olympiad=270 B. C.; aremarkably violent one under Antoninus Pius (A. D. 138-1
61) andagain under Constantine and later. But Leonardo expressly speaks ofan earthquake "_nel mar di Atalia presso a Rod
i_", which issingular. The town of Attalia, founded by Attalus, which is what heno doubt means, was in Pamphylia and mor
e than 150 English milesEast of Rhodes in a straight line. Leake and most other geographersidentify it with the present
town of Adalia. Attalia is rarelymentioned by the ancients, indeed only by Strabo and Pliny and noearthquake is spoken o
f. I think therefore you are justified inassuming that Leonardo means 1489". In the elaborate catalogue ofearthquakes in
